The paper proposes a method for learning node embeddings in a low dimensional space, which is a common problem in network analysis. The proposed method combines matrix factorization and random walk-based models, which are both popular approaches in this field. The main contribution of the paper is the use of kernel functions on the computation of the embeddings, which allows for more flexibility and better performance. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), which is the main focus of the paper. Other likely sub-categories include cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SD (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), which are all relevant to the problem of node embeddings in network analysis.
